## 🦠 Disease Surveillance & Public Health

> Tools used by US public health departments to track, predict, and respond to disease outbreaks.

- **[CDC Open Data Portal](https://data.cdc.gov/)** — Free datasets from the US Centers for Disease Control. Flu, COVID, chronic disease, vaccinations, cancer, mortality, and more. Updated regularly.
  > *The authoritative source for US public health data.*

- **[HealthMap](https://www.healthmap.org/)** — Free real-time disease outbreak tracker. Uses AI to scan news and reports in 15 languages. Built by Harvard/Boston Children's Hospital.

- **[Epi Info (CDC)](https://www.cdc.gov/epiinfo/)** — Free epidemiology software from the CDC. Statistical analysis, data entry, and mapping for public health investigations. Public domain.

- **[EpiNow2 (R Package)](https://github.com/epiforecasts/EpiNow2)** — Free R package for real-time epidemic tracking. Used by US state health departments during COVID-19 to estimate transmission rates.

- **[US Census Health Data](https://www.census.gov/topics/health.html)** — Free population health data from the US Census Bureau. Use it to identify health disparities by geography, race, income, and insurance status.

- **[County Health Rankings (RWJF)](https://www.countyhealthrankings.org/)** — Free annual rankings of health outcomes and factors for every US county. Great for identifying where to target community health interventions.

